## You Built a GPT

Across the last 14 notebooks, you built a complete GPT-2 style language model from scratch. It can tokenize text, embed tokens, attend to context, predict the next token, train on data, and generate text.

That architecture — published by OpenAI in February 2019 — is the foundation of every large language model that followed. But the field didn't stop there.

This notebook is a **map of what changed** between GPT-2 and the models you use today (LLaMA, Mistral, Gemma, Claude, GPT-4). The good news: the core architecture is remarkably stable. The changes are targeted improvements to specific components — and you already understand every component they're improving.

## What Stayed the Same

The fundamental recipe hasn't changed:

- **Decoder-only transformer**: stack attention + MLP blocks, predict next token
- **Residual connections**: `x + F(x)` through every block
- **Attention**: queries, keys, values, causal masking, softmax
- **The training recipe**: cross-entropy loss, AdamW optimizer, cosine LR schedule
- **Autoregressive generation**: one token at a time, left to right

If you understand the v1 model you built, you understand ~80% of any modern LLM. The remaining 20% is targeted upgrades to individual components.

## What Changed (and Why)

Here's the timeline of key changes, and which notebooks in the v2 arc cover each one:

