## The Four Big Upgrades

### 1. LayerNorm → RMSNorm (Simpler Normalization)

**Your v1 model**: LayerNorm subtracts the mean *and* divides by standard deviation. Has learnable scale (γ) and shift (β) parameters.

**Modern models**: RMSNorm only divides by the root-mean-square. No mean subtraction, no learnable parameters. Zhang & Sennrich (NeurIPS 2019) showed the mean subtraction was dispensable.

**Why it matters**: 7-64% faster with no quality loss. Every parameter and every FLOP saved compounds across billions of tokens.

### 2. Learned Positions → RoPE (Rotary Position Embeddings)

**Your v1 model**: A lookup table of 1024 position vectors. Position 1025 doesn't exist.

**Modern models**: RoPE encodes position by *rotating* Q and K vectors. The dot product between rotated vectors depends only on the *difference* in positions, not the absolute positions.

**Why it matters**: No sequence length ceiling. This is why Claude can handle 200k tokens, Gemini can handle 1M tokens, and GPT-4 can handle 128k. Your v1 model would crash at position 1025.

### 3. Multi-Head Attention → Grouped-Query Attention (GQA)

**Your v1 model**: Every head has its own Q, K, and V projections. With 12 heads, that's 12 separate K and V caches during generation.

**Modern models**: GQA shares K and V across groups of heads. LLaMA 2 uses 8 KV heads shared across 32 query heads — a 4x reduction in KV cache memory.

**Why it matters**: The KV cache is the main memory bottleneck during generation. GQA lets you serve longer conversations and more users per GPU.

### 4. Character Tokens → BPE (Byte Pair Encoding)

**Your v1 model**: Each character is a token. Vocabulary of 65.

**Modern models**: BPE merges frequent character pairs into subword tokens. "the" is one token, not three. Vocabulary of 32k-100k.

**Why it matters**: Same text in ~4x fewer tokens. The model "sees" more context per forward pass and trains more efficiently.

## Side-by-Side: v1 vs v2 Architecture

| Component | v1 (GPT-2 Style) | v2 (Modern) | Why |
|-----------|------------------|-------------|-----|
| **Normalization** | LayerNorm (mean + std) | RMSNorm (magnitude only) | Faster, simpler |
| **Norm placement** | Pre-norm | Pre-norm | Same |
| **Position** | Learned lookup table | RoPE (rotation) | No length ceiling |
| **Attention** | Multi-Head (MHA) | Grouped-Query (GQA) | Less memory |
| **MLP activation** | GELU | ReLU² or SwiGLU | Better gradients |
| **Tokenization** | Character-level | BPE subwords | More efficient |
| **Attention extras** | None | QK norm, sliding window | Stability, speed |
| **Generation** | Recompute everything | KV cache | Much faster |
| **Training** | AdamW + cosine LR | Same | Unchanged |
| **Architecture** | Decoder-only transformer | Same | Unchanged |

The bottom two rows are the key insight: **the training recipe and fundamental architecture didn't change**. Everything you learned about attention, residual connections, loss functions, and optimizers applies directly to modern models.

## The v2 Roadmap

Here's what we'll build in the remaining notebooks:

1. **BPE Tokenization** — subword tokens, the merge algorithm, encoding/decoding
2. **RMSNorm** — the simpler normalization
3. **RoPE** — rotary position embeddings
4. **Modern Attention** — grouped-query attention, QK norm, sliding window
5. **The Modern Transformer** — putting the upgraded components together
6. **KV Cache** — fast autoregressive generation
7. **Conversation & SFT** — from language model to chatbot
8. **Serving with LiveView** — deploying your model as a web app

Each notebook swaps one component of your v1 model for the modern version. By the end, you'll have a model architecturally equivalent to LLaMA/Mistral — the same models running on millions of devices today.

## What's Next

We'll start with the most user-visible change: **BPE tokenization**. Instead of one character per token, you'll build a tokenizer that learns to merge common pairs of characters into subwords — the same algorithm used by GPT-4, LLaMA, and every modern LLM.
